        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Oh quid moror? Hoc age: nihil scripturiens, n&eacute; gry quidem: sed tantummod&ograve; lecturiens: quanta potes tam 
                        solerti sagacitate, qu&agrave;m avida, alacriq[ue] apprehensione. Nam penit&ugrave;s singula eruenda, confestimq[ue] 
                        expedienda ex istis Romanarum antiquitatum monumentis. Sed scribendi hoc vulgare cacoethes, lectores facit saep&egrave; 
                        pigros, actores, pla[e]runq[ue] ignavos. Sapientiores Socratici, qui maluerunt
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="EL">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>ἄγραφα ῥητα μνημονικὰ.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
                        <language ident="LA">
                            <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                                <marginalia_text> Manum de tabula, inquit ille. Pennam de manu, inq[uam] ego. Iam ad Phoenicem: sed solis [sic, instead of solum] oculo.</marginalia_text>
                            </position>
                        </language>
            <translation>Why am I delaying so? Pay attention and do not desire to write, not even the least trifle, but only desire to read, 
                as much as you can, with equally clever keenness as eager and perceptive understanding. For individual issues must be fully dug 
                out and immediately extricated from those monuments of Roman antiquities. This vulgar bad habit of writing often makes readers 
                dilatory and usually makes actors cowardly. The followers of Socrates were wiser: they preferred teachings that were unwritten, 
                spoken, preserved by memorization. “Take your hand from the picture,” runs the old saying. “Take the pen from your hand,” 
                so runs my saying now. Now on to the Phoenician, but with the eye *only [*'solis' read as 'solum']. 
                [Grafton and Jardine, 1990, supplemented]
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
